								<h4>Software Definition</h4>																		
								<p>Computers are machines. Just like you can control the climate in your house with air conditioning (which is a machine) by setting the temperature, you can control information by using a computer. It a machine that does what the programs installed on it instruct it to do or what the user (you) tell it to do. Some programs are installed at the factory where the computer is made (like the start up program we talked about in the booting up section) and some are installed afterwards (like games) because a user chooses to do so.</p>
								<p>The programs that instruct the computer to do a certain job are grouped together and called <strong>software</strong>. There are two major types of computer software:</p>
								<ol>
									<li><strong>System Software</strong></li>
									<li><strong>Applications Software</strong></li>
								</ol>
								
								<hr>
								
								<h4>System Software</h4>
								
								<p><strong>System software</strong> is a general term that refers to a group of programs that operate the computer hardware, store and process data, and provide a place or <strong>platform</strong> on which to run application software.</p>
								<p>The terms, <strong>system software, operating system, file management, and user interface</strong>, can all be used to refer to the program that you encounter when you first turn on the computer. A very common example is Microsoft Windows. Different terms are used for different reasons, so let's review each one to understand it more clearly.</p>
								<p>System software is a group of programs.</p>
								<p><strong>Operating System Software</strong> is the most basic software installed on your computer and it provides the overall structure function of the machine. The operating system software is always running in the background and it controls and directs the flow of information and data from within the computer.</p>
								
								<p>There are different kinds of operating systems such as Microsoft Windows, Linux, or Mac OS. The operating system is an important part of the computer's basic makeup and acts as a "bridge" between your computer hardware and the application software. Windows, Windows 95, Windows XP, Vista, and Windows 7 are all versions of the Microsoft Windows operating system.</p>
								<p><strong>File Management Software</strong> is a term that describes the programs you use to create, organize, delete and manage files and folders and the data stored within them. There is a whole unit in Jump Start where you will learn about using files and folders in more detail.</p>
								<p><strong>User Interface</strong> is used when talking about "the look and feel"ù of the interaction between the computer and the user. An easy example of this is your desktop. As you learned earlier, the desktop has icons, a taskbar, windows, a mouse pointer and more. All of these user friendly pieces together make up what is called a Graphical User Interface, or GUI for short.</p>
								
								<h4>Application Software</h4>
								<p><strong>Application software</strong> are programs that allow the user to do a particular task on the computer such as getting on the Internet, creating a document, playing a game, looking at a map, listening to music and many, many other things.</p>
								<p>The examples of application software are almost endless! Common examples are Google Maps, Microsoft Word, iTunes, Photoshop and so many more.</p>
								
								<h4>Hardware Definition and Types</h4>
								<p>The computer software you learned about in the previous section runs on computer hardware. <strong>Computer hardware</strong> means all of the physical parts of the computer. There are many types of hardware, but we will focus on these five:</p>
								<ol>
									<li>Motherboard</li>
									<li>Processor (CPU)</li>
									<li>Hard Disk</li>
									<li>Input Devices</li>
									<li>Output Devices</li>
								</ol>
								
								<p>The <strong>motherboard</strong> (also called the main circuit board) is like the heart of the computer. Every component of the computer is linked to it in some way and it the motherboard that provides the power. You may have heard of <strong>chips or silicon chips</strong>. These are very tiny electronic devices that do much of the work of the computer as well as store data. The motherboard is where these devices are located as well as the computer's processor and the RAM (Random Access Memory - more about RAM in the next section).</p>
								<p>The <strong>processor</strong> (also called a microprocessor or a <strong>CPU</strong>, which is short for central processing unit) is like the brain of the computer and is located on the motherboard. It communicates with all of the other parts of the computer and it is the part of the machine that reads the instructions from the software and computer programs and processes information that has been input into the computer.</p>
								<p><strong>Hard disk</strong> (also called the <strong>hard drive</strong>) is a standard drive on the computer that is installed at the factory. It is a part of the permanent hardware of the computer and is not portable. Users can store large amounts of data here.</p>
								<p>The motherboard, CPU and hard drive are located in the tower on a desktop computer.</p> 

<img src="images/fig1.jpg" alt="Computer Diagram">

<p>In a laptop computer, these components are located in the base, which is the bottom half of the laptop.</p>


<img class="left space" src="images/misc/computer_laptop.png"/>	


<hr>


															
								<p><strong>Input </strong> is any data entered into the computer and <strong>Input devices</strong> are equipment that put the data into a form a computer can process. That form is called <strong>digital information</strong> (which you will read about later). Examples of input devices are the keyboard, the mouse, scanners, microphones, game joysticks and digital cameras.</p>
								
								<img class="left space" src="images/computerbasics/inputdevices.jpg"/>
<hr>								<p><strong>Output </strong> is information produced by the computer and <strong>Output devices</strong> are equipment that translates the information (the <strong>digital information</strong>) that has been input into the computer and processed back into a form that can be read and understood by the user. Some common output devices include the monitor, printer, speakers, headphones, ear buds and portable drives.</p>


<img class="left space" src="images/computerbasics/outputdevices.jpg"/>
