								<h4>Digital Language and Information</h4>
								
															
																<p>With input devices, like the keyboard, mouse, microphone, or digital camera, users put data into the computer. For the computer to be able to understand and use it, the data must be changed into a form that it can understand. That form is <strong>digital language</strong>. The word digit means number, so <strong>digital information</strong> is information converted into a language (or code) made up totally of numbers.</p>
								<p>Just like computers have a special vocabulary (as we talked about in the Introduction), the digital language computers use and understand is special too. It uses only two numbers, the numbers "1"ù and "0"ù and this digital language is called <strong>binary code</strong>.</p>
								<p>Computers are built around the simple idea that <strong>binary code</strong> can be represented by an electrical on/off switch that has just two settings, "on" or "off,"ù like an ordinary light switch that you can flip on or off. Zero represents the "off" state of the switch and one represents the "on" state of the switch.</p>


<p>So, switches hold <strong>digital information</strong>. A switch can either be on or off. If it is off, it represents a 0 and if it is on it represents a 1. If you line up switches together, the switches can be in a variety of states. All of them could be off or all of them could be on or every other one could be on, and so on.</p> 

<p>All stored information on your computer is stored in electrical switches. So, let's learn about what those switches are called and how they are lined up to represent information in a computer.</p>
								
															
								<hr>


