								<h4>Bits and Bytes</h4>
								<p>Each switch is called a <strong>bit</strong> (short for <strong>b</strong>inary dig<strong>it</strong>).  </p>
								
<img class="left space" src="images/computerbasics/bit.jpg"/>
<hr>

<p>The collection of 8 switches is a called a <strong>byte</strong>. The word, byte, does not stand for anything in particular.</p>
	

<img class="left space" src="images/computerbasics/byte.jpg"/>
<hr>

							<p>By using the different combinations of on and off switches (bit configurations) in a byte, any letter, character, or number on the keyboard can be represented. But everyone must agree on what a certain bit configuration represents. The most widely accepted standard for representing characters with 8 bits is the <strong>A</strong>merican <strong>S</strong>tandard <strong>C</strong>ode for <strong>I</strong>nformation <strong>I</strong>nterchange (ASCII pronounced "as-kee").</p> 

<p>Below is a sample of ASCII binary codes:</p>

<img class="left space" src="images/computerbasics/askee.jpg"/>
<hr>

<p>Notice that the capital letter <strong>A</strong> and the lower case <strong>a</strong> have different combinations of on and off switches and are thus two totally different things to the computer. You must be careful to distinguish between upper case and lower case letters when you type an address on the Internet because browsers (application programs that navigate the Internet) are case sensitive.<p/>

<p>The concept of <strong>bytes</strong> and data size becomes important when you get to later sections about computer memory, data storage and beyond. </p>


							<p>All digital information is measured in bytes. But one little byte of data is really small, for example, one letter, number or symbol on your keyboard is one byte of data. Most data is measured in KB and bigger.</p>

<img class="left space" src="images/computerbasics/commonlyusedbytevalues.jpg"/>
<hr>

	
																<p>To sum this up, <strong>all digital information is zeros and ones and is measured in bytes</strong>. Bytes are groups of switches. Digital information is stored in switches, in bytes.</p>


